1
00:00:00,824 --> 00:00:26,274
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa

2
00:00:26,929 --> 00:00:31,117
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:37,887 --> 00:00:47,383
So I thought we'd just have a little contemplation, you might say, around these three words.

4
00:00:47,523 --> 00:00:49,326
Sympathy, empathy.

5
00:00:50,335 --> 00:00:51,136
And compassion.

6
00:00:51,737 --> 00:00:57,844
So I want to quote the Buddha here, talking about himself and his relationship to the monks.

7
00:00:59,067 --> 00:01:06,496
Thus, monks, I have taught you the unconditioned, the destination and the path leading to the destination.

8
00:01:07,438 --> 00:01:17,692
Whatever should be done, monks, by a compassionate teacher, out of compassion for his disciples, desiring their welfare, that I have done for you.

9
00:01:18,230 --> 00:01:20,712
These are the roots of trees, monks.

10
00:01:20,852 --> 00:01:22,275
These are empty huts.

11
00:01:22,995 --> 00:01:23,697
Meditate.

12
00:01:23,996 --> 00:01:27,641
Do not be negligent, lest you regret it later.

13
00:01:28,182 --> 00:01:30,444
This is my instruction to you.

14
00:01:32,727 --> 00:01:44,861
Now, interestingly, whenever he talks about compassion, about himself as a compassionate person, he always uses the word anukampa.

15
00:01:45,685 --> 00:01:49,549
And this word kampati means to tremble.

16
00:01:49,569 --> 00:01:56,337
So the anu is just a reinforcement, shaking, trembling.

17
00:01:56,356 --> 00:02:01,082
And it's what we would, I presume, recognize as empathy.

18
00:02:01,683 --> 00:02:07,170
So it's a sort of resonating with somebody else's heart, with somebody else's suffering.

19
00:02:09,192 --> 00:02:14,959
The usual word that you'll find, of course, is Karuna, which just means compassion.

20
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:21,687
And he's often titled the Mahakaruniko, the great compassionate one.

21
00:02:21,706 --> 00:02:30,397
So if we look at these three words, the sympathy, I think it gets bad press these days, sympathy, in the caring professions.

22
00:02:30,418 --> 00:02:35,925
Well, you can understand that if you're looking after somebody, sympathy doesn't quite make it.

23
00:02:36,530 --> 00:02:41,536
But even in psychotherapy, I think they have a bit of a downer on it.

24
00:02:42,197 --> 00:02:48,064
But frankly, if you were going to feel empathetic about all the suffering in the world, I think you'd burn out.

25
00:02:49,366 --> 00:02:51,429
At least I think I'd burn out.

26
00:02:52,950 --> 00:02:58,997
The danger, of course, is that you're standing too far apart.

27
00:02:59,179 --> 00:03:01,861
You're not actually feeling anything.

28
00:03:02,247 --> 00:03:09,372
And this makes any expression of sympathy sound a bit false.

29
00:03:10,752 --> 00:03:20,204
And also, in that state, you could fall into the error of being judgmental about the person who's suffering.

30
00:03:20,925 --> 00:03:28,835
So if somebody fell off a ladder, you might say, oh, well, you shouldn't have put the ladder there at all.

31
00:03:28,895 --> 00:03:32,258
I mean, you were just asking for an accident.

32
00:03:32,759 --> 00:03:36,625
It doesn't particularly help somebody who's just broken their legs.

33
00:03:39,423 --> 00:03:41,566
So I think there's a place for sympathy.

34
00:03:41,907 --> 00:03:45,252
I mean, when somebody dies, you send a card with sympathies.

35
00:03:45,331 --> 00:03:47,054
You don't send a card with empathies.

36
00:03:48,056 --> 00:03:55,286
So I think it still has some role to play in our relationship to suffering, to people who are suffering.

37
00:03:59,932 --> 00:04:01,836
If you hang about...

38
00:04:02,034 --> 00:04:13,265
certain facts about the world and you allow yourself to become empathetic, then it's a big weight upon you because that empathy moves you towards action.

39
00:04:14,567 --> 00:04:23,694
So sympathy, I think, just has a place of a sort of mild connection, a mild heart connection, just knowing that there's not much you can do about it.

40
00:04:26,218 --> 00:04:28,600
I mean, at the moment, for instance...

41
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:35,247
Every day, it seems, around about 40,000 children die of starvation or hunger-related causes.

42
00:04:36,108 --> 00:04:41,033
If you were to hang on to that, you know, it's a sort of a dreadful, awful figure.

43
00:04:41,733 --> 00:04:46,379
The Buddha in the Dhammapada actually says hunger is the worst of all diseases.

44
00:04:48,920 --> 00:04:51,023
I mean, we don't really feel hunger.

45
00:04:51,083 --> 00:04:56,629
We feel hungry, feel a bit peckish, but we're very quick to sort of fulfill it.

46
00:04:56,778 --> 00:05:11,630
But hunger, knowing hunger, you know, a sort of something that really begins to make you worry about your life that we've never or at least I've never had that sort of hunger.

47
00:05:12,050 --> 00:05:12,411
I did.

48
00:05:13,192 --> 00:05:20,586
There was somebody who came to Candaboda who said that he'd been out in the country and he got he lost his food.

49
00:05:20,646 --> 00:05:21,387
Something happened.

50
00:05:21,668 --> 00:05:22,490
This is in America.

51
00:05:23,252 --> 00:05:27,360
And he got so hungry that when he caught a bird, he just ate it.

52
00:05:27,639 --> 00:05:28,903
He ate it raw.

53
00:05:31,468 --> 00:05:33,552
I couldn't tell you how hungry you can get.

54
00:05:35,269 --> 00:05:43,601
So this sympathy comes from the Greek, which just means to have a feeling with, a community feeling actually, a sympathy.

55
00:05:45,264 --> 00:05:50,291
Empathy, of course, comes from the Greek as well, meaning in, in feeling.

56
00:05:50,771 --> 00:05:57,581
So you're actually much closer to the person in your heart.

57
00:05:58,050 --> 00:06:06,959
Now, I've got something from this social psychologist, Daniel Batson, who's researched empathy, it seems, for decades.

58
00:06:07,759 --> 00:06:09,742
And he says there are eight different concepts.

59
00:06:10,702 --> 00:06:15,047
So I'll read them through and you can decide which one you prefer.

60
00:06:15,807 --> 00:06:19,812
So the first one is knowing another's thoughts and feelings.

61
00:06:21,312 --> 00:06:25,036
That's how some people use empathy, knowing another's thoughts and feelings.

62
00:06:25,574 --> 00:06:49,607
imagining another's thoughts and feelings, adopting the posture of another, actually feeling as another does, imagining how one would feel or think in another's place, feeling distressed at another's suffering,

63
00:06:52,372 --> 00:06:57,442
Feeling for another's suffering, sometimes called pity or compassion.

64
00:06:59,324 --> 00:07:03,452
And finally, projecting oneself into another's situation.

65
00:07:05,036 --> 00:07:08,762
So people use this word with various things.

66
00:07:09,904 --> 00:07:14,093
That one about actually feeling as another does, I think is a dodgy one, isn't it?

67
00:07:14,781 --> 00:07:24,276
I mean, if you have, say, some great sorrow and the person you're telling that to say to them, oh, I know exactly what you feel.

68
00:07:25,038 --> 00:07:30,285
Well, I mean, it's a bit of a jump, isn't it?

69
00:07:30,305 --> 00:07:36,194
And the other one about feeling distress at another's suffering sounds a bit like reactivity.

70
00:07:36,574 --> 00:07:38,577
You know, it's like you're reacting to it.

71
00:07:41,747 --> 00:07:54,002
So there's all sorts of definitions for this empathy, but basically I think it differs from sympathy in that there's a heart, a heart connection, a greater heart connection.

72
00:07:54,860 --> 00:08:05,574
One definition was the ability to appreciate the other person's feelings without becoming so emotionally involved that your judgment is affected.

73
00:08:06,334 --> 00:08:15,125
And I think that's the danger with empathy, that the emotional part overrides your rational part.

74
00:08:15,146 --> 00:08:18,290
There's got to be a balance there.

75
00:08:18,449 --> 00:08:24,057
If you just think about this recent case of this little poor five-year-old boy who fell down a well in Morocco.

76
00:08:24,795 --> 00:08:30,785
hundreds of people sort of watching online, hundreds of people turned up, thousands watching online.

77
00:08:30,824 --> 00:08:32,527
It became worldwide news.

78
00:08:33,688 --> 00:08:39,717
And yet, as I've mentioned every day, 10,000 children are dying of hunger or hunger-related causes.

79
00:08:41,701 --> 00:08:49,572
So there's a point where, you know, something touches you very greatly and it becomes a sort of obsession, really.

80
00:08:51,660 --> 00:08:54,947
Now, you might not feel empathy for various reasons.

81
00:08:55,609 --> 00:09:03,744
One of them is, you know, fear and aversion towards another's suffering that keeps you away from it.

82
00:09:04,586 --> 00:09:13,062
And if that comes to us, then really we have to do a bit of vipassana on it and wait for it to pass and make that effort to connect.

83
00:09:13,952 --> 00:09:17,840
Um, I was once walking on a, on a, on a main road.

84
00:09:17,860 --> 00:09:19,363
This is going back many, many years.

85
00:09:19,943 --> 00:09:22,028
And, um, a dog had been knocked over.

86
00:09:22,048 --> 00:09:31,063
It was dark at night and, uh, it was obviously in agony and whoever had knocked it over and put it under a tree.

87
00:09:32,427 --> 00:09:37,075
Um, and I was with my ex-wife at that time and, uh,

88
00:09:37,408 --> 00:09:41,052
I went to try and make the dog comfortable.

89
00:09:41,493 --> 00:09:48,821
And as I lifted it a little bit to try and get it into a better position, it just grimaced with this dreadful pain.

90
00:09:49,822 --> 00:09:51,844
And I didn't know what to do, really.

91
00:09:52,144 --> 00:09:54,147
So we just left it.

92
00:09:54,807 --> 00:09:58,591
I mean, these days, of course, with mobiles, you'd have got in touch with the RSPCA.

93
00:09:59,673 --> 00:10:05,778
But it was sort of imprinted on my mind, the dreadful agony that this poor dog was in.

94
00:10:08,475 --> 00:10:15,647
The other thing is pity.

95
00:10:16,948 --> 00:10:19,552
Pity is sort of feeling sorry for someone.

96
00:10:20,214 --> 00:10:36,558
It's really coming from a place of conceit, you know, and it stops you really feeling what you're really hiding your feeling for that person by covering it over with a sense of being sorry for someone.

97
00:10:37,365 --> 00:10:42,211
Well, I mean, we've all, I'm sure, had that experience of somebody feeling sorry for us.

98
00:10:42,791 --> 00:10:43,812
It's not very helpful.

99
00:10:44,812 --> 00:10:51,860
But it's one way that we can, as it were, bypass that feeling of being connected to somebody's suffering.

100
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:55,123
If it's something that we find very difficult to be with.

101
00:10:57,966 --> 00:11:00,028
And the final thing is moral outrage.

102
00:11:01,950 --> 00:11:07,034
You know, people being outraged by the dreadful things that are going on in society and things like that.

103
00:11:07,875 --> 00:11:18,929
And I was just reading that there are recent studies where for celebrities, it's very good for publicity to be morally outraged.

104
00:11:20,250 --> 00:11:22,955
And then social media content loves it.

105
00:11:22,975 --> 00:11:28,922
Sharing, retweeting it, expressing this tremendous moral outrage.

106
00:11:32,850 --> 00:11:39,139
But it often sort of disguises a sense of insecurity about one's own moral standing, it seems.

107
00:11:39,981 --> 00:11:48,094
So if you find yourself being morally outraged, just hang on in there for a minute and just ask yourself, well, where's this outrage coming from?

108
00:11:48,173 --> 00:11:49,294
And how is it helpful?

109
00:11:49,836 --> 00:11:54,062
In Buddhist understanding, rage doesn't really help.

110
00:11:54,543 --> 00:11:57,967
It only clouds our minds, clouds our hearts.

111
00:12:00,351 --> 00:12:01,153
And then...

112
00:12:02,062 --> 00:12:14,160
So finally, if the empathy has force behind it, then there'll be a sort of a demand really within ourselves to do something.

113
00:12:14,802 --> 00:12:21,673
And that's when we enter into some sort of compassionate action.

114
00:12:23,375 --> 00:12:26,340
I just think you have to be very careful there, isn't it?

115
00:12:26,360 --> 00:12:40,624
Because often people get burnt out with this stuff, not recognizing that difference between what you can do and what you want to do, who you can influence and who you can't influence.

116
00:12:40,739 --> 00:12:51,072
And if you try to do something which is not within your power or your area of influence, then obviously you're just going to end up burning out.

117
00:12:51,091 --> 00:12:54,294
You're just going to end up feeling disappointed, depressed, and all that.

118
00:12:56,677 --> 00:12:59,061
I've used the word depressed there, which I don't like.

119
00:12:59,140 --> 00:13:00,182
It medicalizes it.

120
00:13:01,323 --> 00:13:03,427
More like disheartened would be a better word, I think.

121
00:13:03,787 --> 00:13:04,587
Down in the dumps.

122
00:13:07,511 --> 00:13:10,375
Here's a little thing that might be of interest.

123
00:13:10,844 --> 00:13:18,111
If you're a bit down in the dumps and you feel a bit low, you might give yourself a little present, you know.

124
00:13:19,373 --> 00:13:20,394
And that makes you feel happy.

125
00:13:20,414 --> 00:13:21,215
It lifts you a little bit.

126
00:13:21,936 --> 00:13:27,763
I suppose it comes to, what do they call it, retail therapy or something.

127
00:13:27,783 --> 00:13:38,995
But how interesting it is that when you see somebody who's a bit down in the mouth and you want to give them a bit of a lift, doing a little kindness to them, your happiness stays much longer.

128
00:13:40,087 --> 00:13:50,962
And it tells us about how we relate to each other and how important it is for us to have that sort of kind relationship.

129
00:13:57,852 --> 00:14:05,903
So I just want to end with just this little occasion that happened to me and what responses I might have given.

130
00:14:06,284 --> 00:14:07,826
I won't tell you which one I did.

131
00:14:08,567 --> 00:14:09,909
That wouldn't be fair.

132
00:14:10,918 --> 00:14:14,464
So I got on a bus once and I sat next to this elderly man.

133
00:14:14,664 --> 00:14:15,566
Again, this is going back years.

134
00:14:16,106 --> 00:14:19,712
And his face was very badly injured and scarred and bruised.

135
00:14:20,714 --> 00:14:24,340
And I asked him, I said, what happened?

136
00:14:25,020 --> 00:14:31,630
And he said he'd been worrying about his rent and he walked out in the road and got knocked over, got knocked down.

137
00:14:34,034 --> 00:14:36,639
So, I mean, I could have said things like, well, that's bad news.

138
00:14:37,500 --> 00:14:39,322
Well, that's what happens when you get worried, you see.

139
00:14:40,399 --> 00:14:41,380
Well, at least you weren't killed.

140
00:14:45,988 --> 00:14:49,433
I could say something like, well, you know, I'm very sorry to hear that.

141
00:14:49,453 --> 00:14:53,379
But, you know, the Citizens Advice Bureau, they can really help you with money problems.

142
00:14:56,224 --> 00:14:58,267
That would be particularly helpful.

143
00:14:59,428 --> 00:15:01,772
I might say, well, that's really terrible.

144
00:15:01,851 --> 00:15:03,455
You know, I'm so sorry to hear it.

145
00:15:03,615 --> 00:15:05,057
I do hope you heal quickly.

146
00:15:09,037 --> 00:15:10,960
I might say, I'm very saddened.

147
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:12,221
I'm saddened to hear what you say.

148
00:15:12,302 --> 00:15:14,184
It's a pretty terrible experience.

149
00:15:14,205 --> 00:15:15,307
How are you feeling now?

150
00:15:15,346 --> 00:15:17,109
Are you getting treatment?

151
00:15:18,091 --> 00:15:21,034
Are your rent troubles getting sorted?

152
00:15:21,475 --> 00:15:24,259
And I hope you heal up quickly.

153
00:15:24,520 --> 00:15:26,504
So I've had that little bit of conversation.

154
00:15:27,485 --> 00:15:29,187
I might leave him cheered up a bit.

155
00:15:34,619 --> 00:15:40,157
But then you might step over that line and you might be saying things, the similar things.

156
00:15:40,778 --> 00:15:44,851
But then you say to him, have you asked, do you know where to go for help?

157
00:15:45,332 --> 00:15:48,442
And then you suggest, you know, the Citizens Advice Bureau.

158
00:15:49,570 --> 00:16:06,351
And then you might go a step further, which takes you a little bit into do-gooding, where you say, you know, listen, what I'll do is I'll get in touch with the Citizens Advice Bureau for you and I'll get you to meet them and I'll take you there and do this and do that, whether the person wants it or not.

159
00:16:07,373 --> 00:16:08,875
So this is do-gooding.

160
00:16:09,075 --> 00:16:16,725
A do-gooder is a person who does you the good they want to do you, whether you want it or not, whether you need it or not.

161
00:16:17,683 --> 00:16:22,193
So there's all these various ways that we can relate to somebody's suffering.

162
00:16:24,538 --> 00:16:37,447
Anyway, I hope that gives some food for thought and just allows us, I think, not to fall into, I think,

163
00:16:38,086 --> 00:16:38,746
What can we say?

164
00:16:38,787 --> 00:16:43,995
Not to feel that we have to always do something about somebody's suffering.

165
00:16:45,076 --> 00:16:48,221
You know, we're limited by our circumstance.

166
00:16:48,923 --> 00:16:55,453
And not to feel that we always have to be deeply empathetic every time we hear somebody's suffering.

167
00:16:56,535 --> 00:16:58,840
I just think that sort of burns out.

168
00:17:01,845 --> 00:17:04,548
And that there's a place for just ordinary sympathy.

169
00:17:07,464 --> 00:17:09,627
Well, I don't know whether you agree with me or not.

170
00:17:10,490 --> 00:17:25,051
Anyway, I hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your wise choice between sympathy, empathy and compassion, you will release yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

